<span class="displaytext"><b>arlington, va -- </b>u.s. senator (candidate full)'s presidential campaign today released its latest television ad, entitled "family." the ad highlights (candidate full)'s support for higher taxes and increased government spending that will only put more burdens on america's small businesses and cost jobs. while (candidate full) is the biggest celebrity in the world, that doesn't do much to help american families who are hurting from higher gas prices and the threat of home foreclosure. (candidate full) has proposed an "all of the above" energy plan -- the lexington project -- to produce more energy here in america, invest in renewable energy, create jobs and achieve energy independence. the ad will air in key states. <p><b>view the ad here:</b> <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_3dxdbh9nn4">http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_3dxdbh9nn4</a> </p><p><b><u>script for "family" (tv :30)</u></b> </p><p><b><b><i>anncr: </i></b></b><i>is the biggest celebrity in the world ready to help your family?</i> </p><p><i>the real (candidate last) promises higher taxes, more government spending. so, fewer jobs. </i> </p><p><i>renewable energy to transform our economy, create jobs and energy independence, that's (candidate full).</i> </p><p><b><b><i>(candidate full): </i></b></b><i>i'm (candidate full) and i approved this message.</i> </p><p><b><u>ad facts: script for "family" (tv :30)</u></b> </p><p><b><b><i>anncr: </i></b></b><i>is the biggest celebrity in the world ready to help your family? the real (candidate last) promises higher taxes, more government spending. so, fewer jobs. </i> </p><p><b>(candidate full) has called for higher income taxes, social security taxes, capital gains and dividend taxes, and corporate taxes, as well as "massive new domestic spending." </b>"(candidate last)'s transformation, if you go by his campaign so far, would mean higher income taxes, higher social security taxes, higher investment taxes, higher corporate taxes, massive new domestic spending, and a healthcare plan that perhaps could be the next step to a full-scale, single-payer system. is that what most americans want, someone who will fulfill a (PARTY NAME) policy wish list?" (james pethokoukis, "barack hussein reagan? ronald wilson (candidate last)?" <i>u.s. news &amp; world report</i>'s "capital commerce" blog, <a href="http://www.usnews.com/blogs/capital-commerce/2008/2/13/barack-hussein-reagan-ronald-wilson-(candidate last).html">www.usnews.com</a>, 2/12/08) </p><p><b>(candidate full) would raise social security (payroll) taxes. </b>"(candidate last)'s proposal ... would impose social security taxes on income above $250,000 per year. he would continue to exempt income between $102,000 and $250,000 from social security taxes." (teddy davis, sunlen miller, and gregory wallace, "(candidate last) kisses billions goodbye," abc news' "political radar" blog, <a href="http://blogs.abcnews.com/politicalradar/2008/06/(candidate last)-kisses-bi.html" title="blocked::http://blogs.abcnews.com/politicalradar/2008/06/(candidate last)-kisses-bi.html">blogs.abcnews.com</a>, 6/18/08) </p><p><b>(candidate full) would raise income taxes.</b> (candidate last): "[i] would roll back the bush tax cuts for those making over $250,000." (sen. (candidate full), cnn (PARTY NAME) presidential candidate debate, manchester, nh, 6/3/07) </p><p><b>(candidate full) would raise capital gains and dividend taxes.</b> "sen. (candidate last)<b>wants to raise the long-term capital-gains rate for families making more than $250,000 to around 20 percent or somewhat higher but not above the 28 percent level it reached during the reagan presidency, an <a name="orighit_1"></a><a name="hit_1"></a>(candidate last) economic adviser says. the same rate would apply to most <a name="orighit_2"></a><a name="hit_2"></a>dividend income for these investors." (tom herman, "tax report your tax bill: how (candidate last), (candidate last)<b>differ," <i>the associated press</i>,